United Kingdom":"Holwell, Dorset, England, United Kingdom","Dorset, England, United Kingdom":"Dorset, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Aukhurst","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Akehurst  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Akehurst","meanings":["English (Sussex): habitational name from Akehurst Farm in Hellingly, Sussex, named from Old English <i>āc</i> ‘oak’ + <i>hyrst</i> ‘wooded hill’. The modern spelling of the placename is Oakhurst."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Aukhurst was born about 1450, in Dorset, England, United Kingdom, her father, Edward Ackhurst, was 26 and her mother, Elizabeth Wildish, was 26. She married John Edward Watkins VI about 1472, in Holwell, Dorset, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died about 1487, in Holwell, Dorset, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 39."},"et":{"about 1450–about 1487":"umbes 1450–umbes 1487","1450–1487":"1450–1487","1438–1498":"1438–1498","1473–1527":"1473–1527","1425–1500":"1425–1500","1425":"1425","1500":"1500","1498":"1498","1487":"1487","1473":"1473","1t Q 1887":"jaanuar 1887","1450":"1450","about 1487":"umbes 1487","1527":"1527","about 1450":"umbes 1450","about 1472":"umbes 1472","1438":"1438","Holwell, Dorset, England, United Kingdom":"Holwell, Dorset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Dorset, England, United Kingdom":"Dorset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1450–about 1487":"noin 1450–noin 1487","1450–1487":"1450–1487","1438–1498":"1438–1498","1473–1527":"1473–1527","1425–1500":"1425–1500","1425":"1425","1500":"1500","1498":"1498","148